<section xml:id="designing-classes_vocabulary" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Vocabulary</title>
<p><dl>
<li>
<title>class:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>class</h></idx>
In <xref ref="theway">Chapter</xref>, we defined a class as a collection of related functions.
Now you know that a class is also a template for a new type of object.</p></li>
<li>
<title>instance:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>instance</h></idx>
A member of a class.
Every object is an instance of a class.</p></li>
<li>
<title>instantiate:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>instantiate</h></idx>
Create a new instance of a class in the computer's memory.</p></li>
<li>
<title>instance variable:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>instance variable</h></idx>
An attribute of an object; a non-static variable defined at the class level.</p></li>
<li>
<title>information hiding:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>information hiding</h></idx>
The practice of making instance variables <c>private</c> to limit dependencies between classes.</p></li>
<li>
<title>constructor:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>constructor</h></idx>
A special function that initializes the instance variables of a newly constructed object.</p></li>
<li>
<title>shadowing:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>shadowing</h></idx>
Occurs when a local variable or parameter has the same name as an attribute.</p></li>
<li>
<title>client:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>client</h></idx>
A class that uses objects defined in another class.</p></li>
<li>
<title>getter:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>getter</h></idx>
A function that returns the value of an instance variable.</p></li>
<li>
<title>setter:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>setter</h></idx>
A function that assigns a value to an instance variable.</p></li>
<li>
<title>override:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>override</h></idx>
To replace a default implementation of a function, such as <c>toString</c>.</p></li>
<li>
<title>instance function:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>instance function</h></idx>
A non-static function that has access to <c>this</c> and the instance variables.</p></li>
<li>
<title>identical:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>identical</h></idx>
References to the same object (at the same location in memory).</p></li>
<li>
<title>equivalent:</title>
<p>
    <idx><h>equivalent</h></idx>
Objects that are equal in value, as defined by the <c>equals</c> function.</p></li>
</dl></p>
</section>
